Text.Value: Perhaps you'll understand me better when you know the truth of my condition.
But at what cost?
I can see the answer in your eyes. And that's why I'm leaving.
Go to sleep. If another knife awaits in the night, so be it.
Quiet whining. You're killing the mood.
I thought the orb to be the greatest of my sins, but I see now there are darker depths to which I might yet sink. You may be content to sink into that abyss, but I assure you - I am not.

EditorData.NodeContext: Stern/grim - not impressed with the player's recent behaviour. Ending the conversation.

Text.Value: Yes. And I got you the Idol of Silvanus along the way.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Gale consumed the idol after it was picked up after the Tiefling betrayal, but before this dialogue.

Text.Value: Precious little love lost between us, isn't there?
No - a night like this is unfit to bear witness to such a tale. It's unfit for most things. Now please - permit me some peace amidst this vile revelry. We'll speak, but another time.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim, deeply unhappy with everything that's happened (including having to endure a party of drunken goblins). Firmly but politely telling the player to go away.

Text.Value: How does it feel to kill a woman still flush with the warmth of your body? All par for the course for you, I suppose.
Two shadows are darkening my soul. The shadow within and the shadow without:
What chances I have, I'll take them. I'd rather roll the dice than deliver all this death.
Go on then. There's no time like the present.
You make your own choices. Don't blame me for their outcomes.
Farewell.
Betrayed by a drow commander of the Absolute. How unexpected a turn of events.

EditorData.logicalname: Character still around after Drow Betrayal

Text.Value: You will. But not until then. Now please - I'd prefer to be alone with my regrets. Enjoy these vile revelries, if that's your inclination. It certainly isn't mine.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grim, deeply unhappy with everything that's happened (including having to endure a party of drunken goblins). Firmly but politely telling the player to go away.

Text.Value: Yes. And I got you the Idol of Silvanus along the way.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Player collected the Idol after betrating the Tieflings but hasn't given it to Gale yet.

Text.Value: At what cost? Are our lives truly worth so many others?
You.
You led me down this path.
I'm sorry you feel that way.
You don't stand a chance alone. You're free to go. I dare you.
This is the worst moment. When the screams of the dying have faded, and the conquering hordes howl and yelp as they come to their vile climax.
Don't blame me for detesting them.
They're the hands they always were. You've a knack for this.
Then leave.
Massacre. A spectacle of slaughter. And I participated.
What are these bloody stumps that used to be such delicate harpists of the Weave?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: He looks at his hands in Lady Macbeth fashion knowing that he participated in the destruction of the grove.
EditorData.NodeContext: He looks at his hands in Lady Macbeth fashion knowing that he participated in the destruction of the grove.

Text.Value: Yes. Yes, I suppose we do. Few things are more powerful than the will to live.
It's time to stop making excuses.
I guess I'll find out, when you're ready to tell me.
Gods damn you - you're right. Few things are more powerful than the will to live.
I've said my piece. Now let me dull my tongue with wine.
All the more blood.
You really are absolutely heartless, aren't you?
I don't know myself anymore. All this... It's not who I am. Around you, I'm not who I want to be.
Stay. We make each other stronger. We make each other survive.
I should leave.
Perhaps we've gone too far, but what's done is done.
But no matter. What's one more kill but a fitting coda to a day of carnage?
You've seen your own true nature. Accept it.
No!
But carnage such as this... The shadow within is spreading like poison, corrupting kindness and compassion.

Synopsis: The player sided with the drow and goblins and participated in the massacre of the grove. Gale is shocked by what happened and the fact that he participated in the slaughter. He wants to leave, so the player has to convince him to stay if indeed he wants Gale to stay. The mood and tone are dour and dark.
